 A hybrid hunt engine fits what you described because it can preserve a clear beginning/end while still allowing branching routes, shortcuts, detours, keys, checkpoints, and optional side systems without turning every hunt into a huge branching tree. That matches the general distinction between linear narrative, branching narrative, and systems that keep a main path but allow controlled deviations.

The three models
Linear means the hunt is basically one authored path from start to finish. It is easiest to build and debug, but it is the least flexible for things like sponsor shortcuts, maze bypasses, or optional reward routes.

Dynamic means the engine can freely redirect the player based on conditions, state, or procedural rules. That gives you the most flexibility, but it can become hard to author, test, and keep feeling coherent unless you put strong guardrails around it.

Hybrid means you keep a mostly authored main route, but allow controlled deviations: alternative routes, trap outcomes, portals, key gates, rewards, and conditional bypasses. That’s the best fit when you want a beginning and end, but also want player choice and route variation.

